<br>
My Husband has been called away on yet another mission for the peoples of the West.  His parents and <br>
mine are as uncaring for our families needs as ever.  I know in my heart of hearts that Gavin is one of the few men in the West that can succeed in these missions.  His talent for diplomacy, and his ability to command make him almost unique among our peoples.  But I do wish that his missions didn't carry him so far away, and for so long.  The winter nights are very long this year it seems and the cold bites with steel in its teeth.  In all my years living in the Hills of Qeynos never have I known such bitter cold.  My child is restless in my whom, and I pray to Radcet daily for my beloved, and his safe return.  Oh how I miss you Gavin.  I pray to the Healer, and to the Tribunal for your safe return before our son arrives.<br>
<br>
From the Diary of Gavin Macalister<br>
<br>
High Keep: The Winter of the Vox<br>
  I looked down on the dark forest of Kithicor from the Ramparts of High Keep once again.  As I looked into the foggy gloom of the wood I forgot the insulting indifference of the High King to the Halas delegation.  Shalia would always pop into my mind with her wry smile, and impish nature when I was in such a mood but for some reason my ghostly self appointed guardian decided to leave me be on this night.  I found that a bit odd, but in my reasoning I figured it was due to my proximity to the Vale, the land of her birth.  <br>
  The night air was heavy with fog, and bitter with Cold.  The cold was unlike that of my home in the Tundra; it was of an evil fetid nature that clings to all it touches.  I was chilled to the bone beneath my bearskins, and armor.  There was more to this chill then temperature.  There was malice, and loathing.  A loathing I have felt before, and knew to be from evil the rotting hatred the dead held for the living.  My father in law had said to me that there was something very wrong in the stars.  A dark time was upon us, and the balance to all things had been swayed.  He told me that the stars that represent Inoruuk were moving into Mar, and Tanare.  War was coming.<br>
  There was a sudden screech from the wood below that brought my attention back to the moment as I stood there on the ramparts followed by a feint sound.  &quot;Thruum Thruum Thruum  OoooooooooOOooooooooo Thrum Thrum Thrummm Thrumm&quot; came the sound ever increasing in its intensity.  I was not alone in hearing it.  The guard posted in the tower to my left on the ramparts ran toward me, and halted at my side.  The sound was drawing closer now, and a strange howl was mixed in with it.  But the Howl was dull, and coming for our rear.  The guard ran back to his post and began sounding his alarm.  For all the arrogance, and indifference of the King of Antonica I could not argue with the efficiency of the High Keep Guards.  These were the elite of Human Infantry.  Not even the Guard force of Antonious Bale was it's equal in Martial prowess.  The fog below concealed the source of the sound from us on the ramparts, but it was becoming more, and more obvious that it was a moving army.  That Army was approaching the Gates of the lower pass.  <br>
  The captain of the watch raced up the steps to the Tower to my left.  Hot on his heals were the on duty guard force for the eastern ramparts.  The troops of High Keep were alert......<br>
  <br>
From the Diary of Arianna Macalister,<br>
<br>
I could hear the War Horns of the Knights of Thunder scream in the Winter Night as the first pain of my coming child hit me.  Gavin's protector stood at the foot of my bed as I let loose another scream.  There was something wrong, and we both knew it.  She looked at me nervously and then disappeared.  I heard another War horn break the silence of the night. This one was deeper in pitch, and came from the north.  My baby moved again, and I could feel the flesh tare....I screamed then all was black.<br>
<br>
<br>
From the Diary of Gavin Macalister.<br>
<br>
My Halas companions joined me on the wall as the first elements of the approaching Army arrived at the lower pass.  My suspicions were correct.  The Sharlok Orcs had assembled an Army.  From the Western side of the pass I was told that a Gnollish Army was approaching as well.  My Farther in Law had read the stars well.  War had begun this dark frigid day.  The Winter of the Vox would be the season to end peace on Norath.  The gods of Chaos had taken advantage of Innoruk's move on Tanare, and launched a full-scale attack.  Then it struck me.  The Vox was awake in her lair.  I had to get home.  I ran from the ramparts at full speed and was met at the bottom of the wall by Shalia.  My Ghostly friend looked afraid.  <br>
&quot;You must get home Gavin, she needs you&quot;<br>
She then disappeared.  <br>
Angus and I gathered our men, and prepared for the long road ahead. We knew that we would have to fight our way through an Army of Gnolls unless we could find a way to get around them.  <br>
  In our rooms in the lower keep we were surprised to find that our ambassador to the High Keep Court waiting for us.  I was even more surprised that he was joined by the King of Antonica.   Clancy Mackalroy introduced the August monarch of the Anonicas to or party and brought us up to date on the plans of the High Keep Royal Guard.  He was also in contact with Antonious Bale, and my parents.  The Vox was awake, and stirring in her lair.  I was ordered back to Qeynos at best possible speed to assemble the Wolves of the North.  We had to prepare for the Vox, and her minions.......<br>
<br>
From the Diary of Arianna Macalister,<br>
<br>
I awoke to the screaming of a child.  I no longer felt my baby within me.  My Father stood at the foot of my bed.  To his side stood Gavin's mother and the Ghost of Shalia now whole again.  She was holding Ardin in her arms.  I was amazed, once I looked upon my son for the first time.  I knew his name before I spoke it, but yet. I never thought of it before.  He looked at me with big brown eyes.  He was beautiful.  My baby was beautiful........<br>
<br>
From the Diary of Gavin Macalister.,<br>
<br>
 Captain Cranston of the Royal Guards escorted my men to the western ramparts.  There at the gates stood a troop of the Antonican Royal Cavalry.  <br>
&quot;My men are going to make a hole for ya boys.  I understand that you Halas shaman can run like Wolves.  Well, ya better be telling the truth.  My men are only going to hit um once.  Make a hole, and retreat.&quot; Colonel Williamson told us.  <br>
&quot;Don'tcha worry about us lad, we'll be a running faster then those nags yourr boys be sittin on.  Besides that lad, we will no be using that hole.  We're going into the lower pass from the ramparts.&quot;  Clancy Mcloia exclaimed to the Col.  &quot;I'll be passin the blessin's of the Tribunal on yer horses, and men ifen there are no objections, we have another way aroun da Gnolls. We'll only be needing a distraction&quot;<br>
 With that a pair of Bards joined our group.  One was the Famous Dumire of Freeport.  I had never met the young half elf but I had heard of some of his exploits in the East.  I was relieved that we would be able to travel through the Gnolls with these amazing musicians.  It was said that they could lift a crowd off their feet, and move them faster then the fastest of Horses.<br>
  &quot;Col. Williamson, please do not risk your men anymore then necessary, we only need a brief distraction while we descend into the pass.  The bards will cover us with their songs and speed us by the Gnolls.&quot; I told the Colonel.<br>
&quot;Well, we'll just take out their point then.  There isn't a lot of room on the pass for us to maneuver so will charge, wheel, and retreat to the Keep.  Good luck to you all. If the Vox is awake like they say, the Western lands will need it.&quot; The Colonel turned his charger back to his awaiting troopers, and prepared for our signal.<br>
  <br>
From the Diary of Arianna Macalister<br>
<br>
  I held my son close to me as Shalia led me through the Blizzard to the safety of Qeynos.  My Father, and Mother in Law were close by, and had cast spells of protection and speed to insure our safety along the journey.  In normal times it was a peaceful, and scenic ride to the city.  But on this bitter night the winds were as sharp as a Halberd blade.  Ardin slept despite the goings on around him.   He was warm against my breast.  I found it odd that he seemed to be humming in his sleep as well.  A babe of only a few days, and yet he seemed to already know the ways of tune.  Reanen, my mother in law had cast auguries at Ardin's birth and said that he was touched by the healer, and would know the healing arts in the form of music.  She said his destiny was marked with Silver, and Black auguries.  She said that normally this was a sign of balance but in Ardin's case the Silver was faded.  Reanen was not sure of the significance, but my father was clearly shaken.  He made the sign of the healer, and blessed Ardin.  He then left the cottage to speak with Shalia, and Bandle MacGregor of the Wolves of the North.  <br>
 Bandle had been sent to guard us on our journey to the protection of Qeynos.  The High Chief of the Halas Clans did not want anything to happen to Heir of the Wolf Guard was his only message as he silently took up station outside our door. <br>
  He now stood near me as made our way to the Great Western City.  Shalia was to my left.  She looked at me nervously, and then broke into a trot.  She disappeared into the night Bandle stopped me, and shooed me to his rear.  My Father had a spell on his lips, and Reanen held her spear aloft.  Someone was approaching.  I could hear growling, and snarling as the thing approached.  Bandle drew his massive battle-axe, and brought it down in fell swoop that was interrupted by a sickening squish.  I turned away from the figure that was slumped face first on the ground.  It was a goblin sure, but it was a mere whelp.  More were surely about.  Shalia returned, and warned us if a Patrol of Gnolls passing near us from the Black Burrow Clan.  Our problem was detection.  Father said that there was no way we could let my child fall into the hands of the Vox.  I read some of the auguries as well. She came for him.  My son was the chosen.<br>
<br>
From the Halas Archives.  Tome VII: The Wolfguard<br>
<br>
Two Antonican Bards of note joined the Halas men at the top of the pass.  One, the famous Dumire of Freeport, and the other was a lass named Firestryke from the far away city of Kelethin.  As the bards prepared their songs of travel, and stealth the Antonican Cavalry prepared themselves as massive ballistas, and legions of Archers let loose a deadly rain of missiles on the Gnolls crowding the pass.  The Wolfguard moved the party of Halas warriors, Shaman, and the 2 bards to the Gates. Colonel Williamson gave a signal to the Gatesman, and saluted the officer of the Watch.  The Antonicans were ready.  The officer of the watch gave a silent signal for the Archers and Balista crews to cease-fire.  At that same moment the enormous lower gates flung open.  <br>
  The noise was deafening in the pass as the screams of thousands of the dog like creatures howled and whined as missile after missile penetrated their ranks and left avenues of dead among them.  Then with no warning the gates of the lower pass sprang open and to their horror out poured the renowned Antonican Cavalry with lances lowered.  The huge chargers mowed down the Gnolls like grass.  The lead Gnolls flung themselves from the cliffs in waves to avoid the lances of the Antonicans.  Gavin gave the signal to his party once he seen that the Gnolls were fully engaged with the Cavalry, and the bards launched the party into the pass.  The Halas men gave each other looks of surprise and wonder as the bards with their magical tunes launched the small but hearty band into the air with incredible speed.  It was not long until the party was passing the supply trains of the Gnoll Army that stretched all the way into Eastern Karana.  The sounds of the Battle had long faded as the Party approached the massive West Gate Bridge that spanned the Karana River....<br>
  In the pass Colonel Williamson signaled his bugler to sound the withdraw.  The Antonicans wheeled at the sound of the buglers.  The Antonican losses were light at best.  Only 3 troopers lost in the charge.  The Gnolls did not fair as well.  Their dead littered the pass, and the cavern below.  As the chargers reentered the Gates the Gnolls began to recover from the shock of what just occurred, and began to Howl.  The Gnollish Shamans, and Chieftains checked those that attempted to flee with brutal force.  The tactics worked as the Gnolls recovered from their losses and counter attacked the gates.......<br>
 <br>
From the Diary of Gavin Macalister<br>
<br>
As we passed the Gnollish supply trains I could see the roadside was littered with the corpses of all that stood in the path of this ghastly host of canines.  The bodies were of all races, ages and genders.  I was mortified at the brutality of these beasts.  I willed the fire down from within me.  I felt it reach up from the depths of my soul at the injustice sprawled on the grounds below us.  The bards beat their rhythms with masterful skill as we flew on.  It was just as we were in sight of the Great Western Bridge that I saw a small party of Teir'dal battling for their lives against a large scouting party of Gnolls below us.   Despite the race of defenders, I could not allow another being be torn apart by this monsters.  I signaled to Angus who was running at my side, and I dove down into the Fray.  I caught the Gnolls by surprise as I brought The Langseax of the Wolves down on these foul beasts.  The Gnolls could not bear us for long as Angus and the others joined me.  We were of little help to the party of Teir'dal however.  The small band was all but slain.  A young dark elf woman held a bundle close to her breast as she lay bleeding on the ground before several slain Gnolls.  She was barley alive, and I could see that her wounds were mortal.  The looked upon me with desperate fear as she clutched her babe with one arm, and fought with her impending fate to wield a dagger with the other.  I sheathed my great sword and kneeled close to the dying woman. &quot; Fear me not, woman on the Drow&quot; I said to her in Elvish.  &quot;You are mortally wounded, I would not harm such a one save to ease your pain&quot;<br>
  &quot;You are the enemy of my race Barbarian, yet you would grant mercy to me and my child?&quot;  She looked through her pain as she spoke her words with what remaining strength she possessed.  <br>
&quot;There is no honor in harming the wounded dark lady, if you ask I will make your end quick to save your suffering.  Otherwise you will receive no harm from me or my allies.&quot;<br>
  She dropped her dagger, and clutched my hand then.  Her babe whined in her arms and then peeked its head from the bundle.  That is the first time I laid eyes on Morteux. <br>
  One of our Shamans gave her a fast potion to ease her pain.  The young mother looked at me with eyes barely open and brimming with tears.  She spoke again softly this time.  I could tell that the end was near.  &quot;Please noble sir.  Care for my child.  Let him know that his mother loved him, and died bringing him to the light of Tanare.&quot; <br>
 I was shocked.  Here, a Teir'dal woman praising Tanare with her finale breath and asking me to care for her child.   If it were not for a dying woman's last wish I would have thought it Drow trickery.  But she then proved without a doubt that she spoke the truth.  As she handed the babe up to me, she also handed me 2 symbols.  One of the all mother, and the other of the healer. A parchment was attached to the symbols as well.  It was an introduction, and a promise of refuge written in my father in law's hand.  It was addressed to Antonious Bale.  I drew my great sword, and kneeled again before the dying woman.  I held the babe close to my breast and swore to him, and to this brave woman that I would defend him until the day I should be called home.<br>
