From the Diary of Arianna Macalister:<br>
<br>
  My father and I, with the help of many friends were able to flush out that white scaled bitch.  She tried again to steal away my sons, she failed.  Gavin and I had little time together as usual.  The Arch Duke and the High Chiefs called upon him to lead the Allied Armies to the eastern pass to prepare for the Muck tail horde coming down the pass from High Hold. <br>
  The winter is still in full swing and another moon has waned since that dreadful flight from the cottage in the teeth of a blizzard.  Ardin and Morteux are both asleep with Shalia standing watch over the cradle.  Since the Northern horde was destroyed Bandl returned to his infantry command with the Wolves of the North.  The cottage is warm, and we have plenty of wood for the fire and provisions since Gavin stopped by to stock up on our supplies and firewood before he left for the pass.  It’s late.  I think I will get some rest.<br>
  <br>
I awoke in a field of soft grass touched with silver drops of due.  The Sky was deep blue with soft cotton buffs touching the sky.  I felt warm and relaxed as I arose from my slumber.  Before me there was a basket of fresh fruit, and lightly spiced mead to break my fast.  As I sat in the meadow and looked out toward the light rolling hills to the east, I realized that I must have been dreaming.  I also realized that I had never been to this place before.  It was so peaceful.  Even the animals seemed docile to the point of domestic tranquility.  After I finished my breakfast I stood up and started out toward the hills to see if I could find out where this I had been taken.  I passed a crystal clear brook while traveling and stopped to bathe.  As I stood putting on my clothes a woman approached with towels and a brush for my hair.  “Good morning Arianna, hast thou slept well?” she said as she hung the towel on a near by branch.  “Yes, thank you.” I replied wondering how this woman knew my name.  She was strikingly beautiful with golden hair and deep blue eyes that matched the sky.  She was plainly dressed in an earth brown dress that was common among the farms throughout Norath, but she carried herself with a silent regalness that bespoke of a much more complex personality then that of a mere peasant.   <br>
  “Once thou hast dressed, I will assist you with your hair my sister.” She said continuing in a formal speech.  <br>
“Excuse me my lady, but I do not know who you are.  May I know your name?” I asked as I began to dress. <br>
  “I am the woman thy husband avenged in the forests of the fey.  My name is Elanna of the House of Firona.” She replied.    <br>
  I noticed as she approached to help me with my hair that she was a High Elven woman.  She kneeled beside me and began to use slow strokes as she brushed out my hair.  She hummed and ancient Elven loves song that I had not heard for since I was a child.<br>
“Elanna, why have I been brought here, and where is here?”  I asked her.  She stopped humming; “Thou hast been summoned by the all mother and the healer.  You are in the Glade of Tunare.”  <br>
 I suppressed the urge to ask why I was summoned.  I remembered the Auguries that my mother in law cast at Ardin’s birth, as well as the prophecies of the Norathian Oracles.<br>
  Elanna finished with my hair and stood up.  “Art thou prepared to meet thy mother, and father so that they may divulge certain truths onto thee?”<br>
“I am.” I replied simply.  Elanna lead me along a soft loam trail through the trees that opened into a small meadow.  Seated in the meadow was a small woman chatting idly with an Armored Cleric of Radcet Nife.  As we approached the odd pair they both stood and faced us.  The cleric bowed low to me and said: “Welcome to the mother of the Light and of the Sacrifice” The woman also honored me in much the same way.  The cleric beckoned me to be seated on the blanket that was laid out on the grass.<br>
“My daughter” the small woman began.  It has finally come to pass when the prophecy which guides us all shall bring about certain events.  Know dearest daughter that I do not assign the task that I am about to place upon thee lightly.  My son Radcet, and I have discussed this sorrowful deed over and over and we were unable to see an alternative.”  As the woman whom I assumed to be Tunare spoke to me I became ever fearful for my sons.  I had a building feeling of dread and loss as the all mother continued to speak.  <br>
“One of thy family will be rested from the earth. Which one is not clear.  Know that thine Husband, and one of thy sons will be safe.  The future for thee, and thy other son is not clear.  You will need to make a choice revered daughter.  That choice may cost you the life of thee, or thine issue.”   I turned to the cleric who stood before me.  “Is this the way father?”  I asked.  “All though it wrings my heart dearest daughter.”<br>
  “If this to be, then I must prepare.  If it please you mother, and you Father, I shall return to my cottage and look after my sons.”<br>
  “Be well daughter, and trust in the guardian, for she will alert you when thy task is impending”<br>
I awoke in the Cottage to the sound of the babies crying in the next room.  Shalia stood at my bed holding my robe for me.  “Ya better get up mistress.  They sound hungry.”  The little woman exclaimed with a warm smile.  I went into the nursery and began to nurse my sons as Shalia stoked the fire that had been banked for the night.  The light of the early morning began to shine in the windows, but it was a dull light of yet another cold and overcast day.  Shalia scampered about the cottage cleaning and opening the curtains to let in what little light the sun was able to force through the interminable cloud cover that seems to have covered Norath for the last several months.  I finished nursing, and placed Ardin and Mort in their crib and went into the kitchen to help Shalia to prepare some breakfast.  <br>
  “How did ya like the grove me lady?” Shalia asked.  I wasn’t prepared for her question, and was a bit startled.  Although I should have realized that the ghostly self-appointed guardian of my sons and husband would know the will of the gods.  She was a Ghost after all.  “It was very beautiful.  I have never known a place that felt so comfortable”<br>
 I replied to her.  “Aye, it is that.  I have lived there on and off since Gavin laid my earthly body to rest.  The all mother seems to always find something for me to do though.” she said with a playful smirk that was her trademark.  We continued through the day taking care of the many chores around the house and then settled in for the night after we put the babies to bed after their evening meal….. <br>
