The Beast swept in from the North on silent wings and descended on the lone cottage on the western sea.  She flared her massive wings and sat facing the door.  The time of prophecy was about to begin.  Her impending triumph written on the white scaly traces of her massive face.  The two woman, one earthly, and one ghostly knew she was there.  Shalia warned Arianna of the beasts approach.  What the beast had not counted on was Arianna’s heart and courage.  Suddenly the door of the cottage burst forth in a cloud of flame and sparks as the Wizardess emerged.  Behind her stood the little thief with the infant boys cradled in her arms. <br>
 “STAND ASIDE WITCH WOMAN, THOU SHALL NOT WITHSTAND MY FURY!” the Vox bellowed at Arianna.  Arianna shielded by a magic barrier raised her hands toward the Dragon;  “LEAVE NOW IF YOU VALUE YOUR LIFE YOU OVERSIZE ALBINO BITCH!”  With that she unleashed a rain of fire that encompassed the great Dragon.  The Vox flinched back from the flames and inhaled deeply in preparation to unleash her furious breath upon the impudent Wizardess.  Shalia seeing the dragon begin to exhale bolted from the cottage to the south toward the city, she looked back to see Arianna casting yet another barrage of fire at the Dragon as the Vox enveloped her in her frosted fury.  Shalia knew she had little time.  Arianna had made her choice and stood before the beast in defiance.  She cast forth spell after spell of devastating flame, but the Vox was only wounded.  “YOU SHALL NOT ENDURE ME WITCH!  GIVE UP THIS FUTILE RESISTANCE AND SUBMIT THY SON UNTO ME AS IT IS ORDAINED!”<br>
  The Vox boomed at the seemingly tiny human woman that so defied the power of the greatest dragon in the entire world.<br>
  Arianna answered with Lightning.  She opened the clouds with bolt after bolt of blazing electricity causing the Vox to reel in pain.  The Vox rose up on her hind legs and let loose another torrent of frost that enveloped the defiant Wizardess yet again.  This time Arianna’s shield fell.  She gasped at the searing pain that brought her to her knees.  She looked back and could barely see Shalia as she fled with Arianna’s two sons toward Qeynos.  With Tears in her eyes she bade them goodbye, as then whispered her last kiss toward the east at her husband.  She then stood up facing the Great dragon yet again despite her crippling wounds.  She knew her fate.  Her choice, and her task complete.  She unleashed her finale fury of lightning against the great beast.  The Vox felt the lighting searing her relentlessly, the pain was intense but she would not be denied her prize.  Limping with a shattered leg and with gaping holes in her right wing she bellowed a finale time.  This time Arianna was washed away in the blazing fury of the torrent of frost.  Her shattered body slammed limply with a sickening thud against the remains of the cottage.  Her task complete she lay still, unmoving and cold.  The Vox sniffed at her body with a weary nudge of her head.  She turned toward the fleeing halfling, but knew that she was to close to the city for her to pursue.  She was denied after all.  Her only solace was the fact that Arianna lay cold at her feet.  She rose, and lifted into the air limping north to her now shattered lair.  She would tend her wounds and return to claim her prize…… <br>
<br>
From The Qeynos Archives Tome CXXVII:  The Battle of Qeynos Hills.<br>
<br>
The now substantial ghost of Shalia approached the gates of Qeynos at a winded sprint.  Clinging to her breast was the issue of Tekin Thantos, and Gavin Macalister. Both boys now sons of the same man, one natural and one adopted after he saved the infant Teir’dal from the clutches of a marauding band of Muck tail Gnolls.  “OPEN THE GATES, The Guardian Approaches!” shouted the Arch Duke as he paced the walls of the City.  The Priests of Life had warned him of the Dragon’s attack on the Cottage of Arianna and Gavin Macalister.  Feeling helpless, and frustrated at not being able to add the daughter of his close friend, the Arch Duke vowed that he would offer protection of the chosen sons of Macalister even if it cost him his life.  Keeping careful watch over Shalia as she entered the gates, Antonious had a company of Guards meet the Halfling woman as she entered.  The guards formed a protective circle around her, and escorted her with her charges to the Palace.  Once there, Antonious left instructions for his staff to have them quartered in the lower apartments of the palace under heavy guard. Three wet nurses were standing by waiting for Shalia as she entered the suite.  Shalia was nervous, but she gave up her charges to the nurses and surveyed the rooms with a careful eye.  Once she was satisfied that the rooms were secure, she finally relaxed but only to fall into a fit of weeping for the loss of Arianna.  She wanted to help desperately, but she knew that if she did Ardin, and Morteux would have been lost.  Shalia looked up to see several Priests of the Church of life enter rooms and take up positions at the door.  Among them were several Paladins fully armed incase of any attacks.  Shalia knew that her task was near completion.  Gavin was returning, Ardin and Morteux are safe.  It was time to rest.  Shalia fell onto the couch near the blazing fire and cried.  Her weeping raked her little body with the mournful loss of her closest friend.  She knew that Arianna was not completely gone, and she watched her ascend into the heavens after her spirit stopped to check on the boys.  But she still mourned her loss.  The boys would not know her.<br>
<br>
  “The chosen ones and their guardian are secure your Grace.” The Commander of the Guard reported to the Arch Duke as he continued to pace the ramparts.  “Has the force from the Church of life arrived in the apartment? The Arch Duke asked the Guardsmen.  “Aye my lord.  They are in the suite even now.  The Halfling woman has gone however.”<br>
<br>
From the Diary of Gavin Macalister<br>
<br>
The northern threat was soundly dispatched.  The northern horde presented little in the way of sport for the great Armies of Qeynos and Halas. The Splitpaw commanders were incompetent at best; the fools didn’t even bother to assume defensive postures when they saw that a vastly superior force surrounded them.  The just attacked until they had no one left to fight.  And then they died.  Once the grizzly slaughter was over we began our march south and were joined by Armies of Eurdin.  <br>
<br>
The next day we broke camp and headed south.  My forces were stretched out all the way to the villages of Halas as we passed through the deep ice valleys of my homeland.  Once we entered the northern reaches of Qeynos hills, I gave orders for my forces to continue south, and broke off from them and headed to the cottage. <br>
  Arianna, and Shalia were busy cleaning and cooking as I approached the house that I built for Arianna and I so many years ago.  Shalia noticing my approach dropped the straw broom that she was sweeping the front porch with and ran into the house.  She emerged with Arianna in tow just as I was tying off my roan stallion to the curb in front of the porch.  I picked up my two favorite women in a big embrace and kissed them soundly.  Shalia giggled as my whiskers tickled her nose as she always did.  Arianna was quick to point out that not only did I need a shave, but a bath too.  She didn’t even want to hear my excuse that I had been campaigning in the north for the last 2 months.  Her only reply was a look of impatience as she motioned toward the back room where I had built a bathing chamber for her.  I will admit here though.  I was a bit fragrant.  Armor is nice to have on during a battle, but it tends to leave you smelling much like an old iron kettle left out of doors for a season or two.  Not to mention the mixed in sweat, and barley cleaned leftovers of several battles that seems to be so unavoidable.  Needless to say, I did not put up much of a fight.  I was beginning to dread sleeping in the same bed with myself.<br>
  After I had washed, and shaved Arianna led me into the dinning room and rather proudly presented me with a feast fit for the Arch Duke.  I was stunned.  For all of Arianna’s intelligence, grace, and wit.   She could never cook worth a damn.  I had a feeling that she may have been either taking lessons, or she managed to find a spell to summon all the fine food that decorated our table.  My stomach told me to keep my quiet.<br>
  After feasting on the copious array of food we sat idly chatting by the fire as we always did during this time of year.  The boys were sleeping and Shalia was off doing what ever a ghost does at that time in the evening.  We retired and reacquainted our selves to one another, as husband and wife are apt to due after a long separation.<br>
  The next morning I reluctantly made my preparations to return to my command.  I awoke just before dawn as I usually do and slipped out of bed.  I set water to boil in the fireplace and stoked up the banked fire.  Then I went out to the stable to tend to my horse.  When I returned to the house Arianna was awake nursing our sons and Shalia was setting the table for Breakfast.  Despite the bitter cold of this unusual winter, the house was warm and comfortable.  It would not have taken much for Arianna to talk me into staying, but she knew as I did that I had to get back to the Army to set the preparations for the upcoming battle.  We ate our breakfast in silence dreading our impending separation. <br>
<br>
From The Qeynos Archives Tome CXXVII:  The Battle of Qeynos Hills.<br>
<br>
The Wolfguard having returned from his day’s leave with his wife inspected the earthworks that were under construction blocking off the pass into Qeynos Hills from the plains of Karana.  The Engineers of the western armies were hard at work breaking into the frozen earth and cutting long spikes for the approaches.  Archers, Infantry and Cavalry were everywhere tending to their equipment as the ever-watchful sergeants trooped the endless tents lining the hastily set up garrison behind the earthworks.   <br>
  “The horde is moving slowly across the Karana river Wolfguard, it will still be a few days before we will have to pull in our pickets.”  The commander of the Qeynos Cavalry reported to Gavin as he walked along the Earth-works inspecting the day’s progress.  “Very good Colonel.  Have your men rest for the rest of the afternoon. They will have much to do in the next few days.”  Gavin instructed the Colonel.  The Colonel saluted and turned to leave only to be replaced by another officer of the Army reporting on the supply trains, and then another officer followed her.  The day progressed in this fashion until late that evening.  The troops were sleeping huddled in their small tents and Sentries guarded the campfires and battlements.  <br>
  The next day was extremely bitter.  The temperature was still dropping when Gavin emerged from his tent just before sunrise.  He could hear the men groaning and stamping their feet as they slowly emerged into the frigid morning at the insistance of the many Sergeants of the Army barking orders.  The engineers were still hard at work though and could be heard struggling to finish off the battlements.  Oxen grunted as they struggled to tow the countless catapults, ballistas, and trebuchets into position.  Gavin was pleased that the Army had preformed so well over the last few months of endless campaigning.  They had little time to get to know one another, much less train in the combined arms strategies of the young general, but with several fresh victories over the Gnolls, orcs, and Goblins that manned the northern horde moral was extremely high despite the sever weather<br>
  Gavin again stood on the almost complete ramparts and looked across the forest of sharpened stakes that adorned the ramps leading up to the forward trenches.  The sun was just cresting the horizon when Shalia appeared before him.  “GET HOME GAVIN, She’s dieing!” was all the little woman said in half shrieking and half sobbing voice that was filled with fear and hopelessness all at the same time.  Gavin’s heart jumped in his chest as a hundred reasons appeared in his mind for the Halfling’s message.  Then it struck him. The Vox had returned. He could feel it.  He turned from the battlements and bolted to the stables.  His staff on his heels as he ran.  Once at the stables, he barked orders to his messengers to set the troops in the trenches, and order the Cavalry, to the north.  Then he mounted his already saddled horse, and started west at a dead run….<br>
<br>
The Following is an extrapolation of the various accounts and history’s surrounding the days during and just after the Battle of Qeynos Hills.<br>
<br>
The Wolfguard took only a day to reach the ruined cottage that he had built on the shores of the Western sea.  His horse near death, he leapt from the foaming beast sprinting the remaining yards to the ruins.  He found his mother Reannin of Halas, his Father, and his father in law the renown Bastin of Qeynos standing near a tribal bier that was erected to hold the remains of his wife, Arianna.  She had been covered in a burial shroud to hide the hideous wounds that were left on her body, but Gavin could tell that she died in immense pain.  His mind shrieked with fury, and of sadness.  Here lay the very center of his life, the mother of his son, and his soul mate.  He turned his face from the bier, drew his massive sword, and started north at a trot.  His father knew that there would be no way to stop the Warrior.  He was in the bezerker state that was common among the men of Halas.  So he trotted after his son.  Reannin also joined the warrior as well as Bastin of Qeynos.  As the quartet moved north at a brisk trot others joined them.  By the time the party reached the gates of Permafrost Citadel they had grown in number 10 fold.  Word had spread with astonishing speed.  Stouthearted heroes, and Heroines from all over Norath were now poised to do battle with the Great White Dragon of Permafrost.  Word of Arianna’s murder at the talons of the beast had inflamed the allies of the west.  <br>
  <br>
<br>
  During this time, the Gnollish hordes struck the forward defenses of the Western Armies.  In the trenches of the western army, battalions of Archers from Surefall Glade leapt up from their hiding places and released sheets of arrows at the charging host.  Howls of pain, and anguish were thundering as the forward ranks of the Gnollish soldiers melted away beneath the hale of yard long steel tipped arrows.  On the flanking cliff Antonious Bale surveyed the army that had been dubbed the forces of the Wolfguard.  Beneath him standing a top the command tent that sat in the middle of the fortifications, the white banner with the outline of a blue Wolf with it’s muzzle up turned in the howl of the Hunt snapped in the breeze.  The Wolfguard was not present, but the commanders of the Armies knew that he was on blood quest of vengeance and kept his colors flying in honor of his late wife.  His wife’s body lay shattered on the bier where the cottage once stood. She died valiantly defending her sons against certain death.  She succeeded in her task however.  She injured the great beast to the point that it was unable to pursue the ghostly protector of the chosen as she made her flight to the safety of Qeynos.  <br>
  <br>
  Wounded both in body, and mind the Vox fled to her now ruined lair.  She was certain that if she could rally her forces while the armies of the west were occupied by the hordes of the Splitpaw she could yet triumph.  She found her once confident generals cowering in the lower depths of the Citadel.  Yet enraged by her failure in the hills of Qeynos, adding to the rage that overcame her at the sight of these cowards, she let her breath rake them, and bellowed her orders for the Goblins, and Giants to protect the gates of the Citadel with their lives while she healed herself, and sent word to her sister of recent events.  She sat in her lair fuming as she cast her spells of healing on herself.  As she lingered on the verge of sleep, one of her Ice Giant priests approached.  He brought word that the Wolfguard was returning to the hills.  She fell asleep with a smile on her face at the thought of the pain she had caused the impudent Barbarian.  His Bitch of a wife had paid the ultimate price for her defiance.  <br>
<br>
  The horde recoiled from it's first attack as the forward elements were nearly destroyed by the unrelenting rain of deadly arrows.  Seeing the futility of a frontal assault, the Gnollish commanders brought forward captured siege engines and began raining large rocks on the Defenders as they huddled in their trenches.  The barbarian infantry raised their great shields above themselves, and as many other defenders as possible. The hail of rocks still took their toll.  Hundreds of men, half elves, and Eurdins fell beneath the terrible rain before a group of Wizards were able to destroy the enemy catapults with explosive balls of fire and ice.  From a top the cliffs the Arch duke ordered the hidden catapults and ballistas of Wolfguard’s army to release their own wrath upon the Gnolls.  He also gave orders for the knights and Antonican cavalry to begin their strikes from the flanks of the Horde.  <br>
  Without knowing that their flanks were about to be assaulted, the Gnollish shaman, with the help of many pickclaw wizards began sending huge waves of fire, and wind at the earthworks before them.  Their efforts were gaining ground as hundreds of the sharpened stakes were thrown into the air, or destroyed.  The wizards, mages, and enchanters of the western army, unable to stop the waves once they were created began to build a wall of ice before the earth works in an effort to shunt the terrible forces.  But just as soon as they started to gain ground a low rumble became audible from the south, and to the north.  The rumble increased in volume, and intensity as the first regiments of the Antonican Cavalry, and the thousands of Knights of the Orders of Thunder, Life, Truth, and Love crested the adjacent hills.  With shrieking horns, and thundering hooves the mounted forces of the western army crashed into the flanks of the horde.  Antonious Bale was awe struck at the spectacle before him.  The silvery clad Knights with their bright blooms were magnificent as they lowered their lances, and charged forward at the Gnolls.  Howls of fear and pain again thundered on the plain as the Gnolls lining the flanks of the horde were swept under the initial charges of the mounted assault.  Seizing this opportunity to deal a fatal blow to the Gnolls, the Arch Duke ordered the Halas infantry to charge.  The painted warriors of the North sprang forth from their trenches in waves.  As the Halas men left the trenches, they were replaced by the Arch Duke’s reserves consisting of five regiments of steel warriors, supported by another three regiments of Surefall Archers.   <br>
  The Halas infantry, brandishing great swords, axes, and spears charged forward at a full sprint and crashed into the forward ranks of the Gnolls. Close behind them came the many casters of the Army who sent forth deadly sheets of fire and Ice that kept the casters of the horde off balance as they attempted to counter with spells of their own.<br>
  The carnage of the fight was grizzly to behold.  The Gnolls were falling by the thousands as the three-pronged attack pressed inward on the horde’s center.  The ground under foot and paw alike became slick with the terrible affects of such a battle.  The once green plane was now crimson with trickles of blood and gore, which later would become rivers.  The slaughter continued into the afternoon until finally accepting defeat the Gnollish commanders sounded the retreat.  <br>
  <br>
  Gavin approached the gates of Permafrost Citadel with his great sword held low, and heedless of any enemy that attempted to bar his bath.  The blood rage was heavy upon him as he tested the healers in his party with his reckless abandon.  The Ice Giants that guarded the entrance were dispatched within minutes as the powerful group of heroes scrambled to protect the seemingly mad warrior.  No one in the party objected to the warrior’s rage however.  Although he was heedless of his own safety, he was even more terrible to the enemy then himself.  As he pushed passed the Ice Giants, he took out huge slices from the Giants legs, and lower abdomen as he passed.  The crippled Giants toppled to each side as the warrior continued on toward his foe hidden deep in the castle.<br>
  Once the party caught up with Gavin at the entry he silently looked around him.  He could see, but could not acknowledge them.  He was still consumed by his rage.  He only stopped at the insistence of his mother to let the others catch up before pressing forward.  Despite the blood rage, Gavin knew that she was right.  Once the parties were all inside the keep, Gavin once again continued his grim advance into the icy halls.  The few goblins that offered resistance were either blasted into dust by the powerful wizards, or sliced in two by one of the many warriors that accompanied the Wolfguard on his quest of blood vengeance.  <br>
 Deeper and deeper they traveled, and now they could here the Dragon roar as they drew ever closer.  Once in the outer chamber of the Vox’s lair a finale ring of resistance was sent against the party.  The Ice giant priests, and diplomats that remained in the lower depths were destroyed with hardly a second thought.  The party was just to strong, and their resolve to great for even the dreaded Ice Giants to endure.  Once this final defense was put aside the many shaman and clerics of the parties, began preparing the warriors with their blessings and spells of protection.  Gavin kneeled before his mother and father to receive the blessing of the tribunal, as his cousin Clancy Macalroy refreshed the war paint that had been partially washed away by his tears and by the exertions, and debris of battle.<br>
  Once again the Dragon Roared, but the Party was uncaring.  The Vox’s magic was still weak from her battle with Arianna, and the party was to strong to heed her complaints.  Once Gavin was prepared with the many blessings and with the fresh markings of a blood Vengeance quester, he squared his shoulders and once again unsheathed his great sword.  Followed closely by his many friends and allies Gavin burst into the Vox’s lair.  She recoiled in fear at the sudden appearance of the warrior even though she knew that he approached.  She had heard the warnings of her shaman regarding the writings in the stars even though she was determined not to heed them. She stared down at the painted faced man, and tasted fear for the first time in her life.  Despite that, and falling back on her towering pride she struck at the warrior with all the might of her terrible breath.  The warrior only flinched slightly as he continued his advance, and brought down his great sword on her forepaw.  The sword bit deep into the paw and nearly severed it.  The Vox reeled, and struck at the Wolfguard once again, this time with her tail.  She struck him with a glancing blow, which Gavin nearly dodged, but the tail had enough force to flatten him to the ground.  And then they were all around her.  The Vox with her attention firmly on the crazed warrior had failed to notice the many other members of his party surround her.  She was assaulted on all sides by every description of fighter and caster. She was pummeled, blasted sliced and stabbed so many times and in so many places that she panicked.  She was stunned by her own fear and could not even try to heal herself.  She spun around and around trying to keep her many assailants away, but to no avail.  Finally, with a great overhand chop the Wolfguard severed her head from her neck with a devastating critical blow.  The icy blue blood washed many of the party back as it sprang forth from the severed neck like a bursting mountain spring.  The body of the great Dragon flailed in the middle of the lair, and then finally settled into a deflated heap.  The murderer of Arianna was dead.  Once the realization of the battles end pervaded on the raging warrior, he fell to his knees, dropping his weapons and screamed his anguish at the gods.  His howl was of that of a lost wolf in great pain and deep sorrow.  His wounds were heavy, but the terrible warrior was uncaring.  His bleeding was not of his body, but of his soul.  His wife dead, and many of his friends, and companions were also slain.  Beside him lay the body of his father, at his side kneeled his soul torn mother immersed in a similar bought of torment.  <br>
<br>
  The celebration of the peoples of Qeynos, Halas, and Eurdin was subdued.  Although the many peoples of the three allied states were elated by their complete victory, they were also deeply saddened at the terrible cost.  The funeral processions seemed endless as the many fallen heroes, and heroines were returned to their final resting places.  The funeral for Argon, and Arianna Macalister had caused many to weep for days.  Many loved the beautiful wizardess, and the powerful mystic.  Gavin so overcome with grief struck out from the lands of the west leaving his sons in the care of the Arch Duke.  He could not face the world with out Arianna.  So he decided that he would seek his own death by going east to join or at least attempt to add the citizens of the Pass in their ongoing defense of their mountain home.  If that did not work he thought to himself, he would find another hopeless quest and on it would go until he could once more be in the arms of the only woman he could ever love.<br>
<br>
 As to the fate of the chosen, well I can tell you first hand that the Vox’s failure was complete.  As it is I, Ardin Macalister, am the author of this final work.  My father was unable to speak of the tail and the many historians who witnessed the events were unable to assemble the story from all the aspects of the battle. So my brother and I took it upon our selves to finish the tale.  My Brother’s task is not complete as yet, but he continues to rally the Teir’dal of good heart to his cause.  I feel that in the end, with the help of our father, and our many allies that he will eventually succeed.   My father however never fully recovered from the loss of his wife, my mother.  He did slow down a bit in his suicidal ambitions, but to no great degree.  He still comes home wounded to the quick.  <br>
  So friends we come at last to the end this tale.  Remember as you go away this night to pray for your fallen heroes, and to honor those that sacrificed for your freedom.<br>
  Goodnight friends, be well in your travels.<br>
<br>
 Ardin Macalister, in cooperation with Morteux Thantos.<br>
